      "subject_input": "What is design thinking and how does it work?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nDesign Thinking is a structured approach to problem-solving that prioritizes understanding real user needs before jumping to solutions. It works through **three spaces** with **nine methods**:\n\n**Problem Space (Methods 1-3)** \u2014 Understand what's actually wrong\n1. **Scope Conversations** \u2014 Classify the request (frozen vs fluid), map stakeholders, discover constraints\n2. **Design Research** \u2014 Interview and observe real users in their actual environment\n3. **Input Synthesis** \u2014 Find patterns across research data, build validated problem statements\n\n**Solution Space (Methods 4-6)** \u2014 Explore how to solve it\n4. **Brainstorming** \u2014 Generate diverse ideas using constraints as creative drivers\n5. **User Concepts** \u2014 Turn ideas into simple visuals stakeholders can react to\n6. **Lo-Fi Prototypes** \u2014 Test scrappy prototypes with real users in real conditions\n\n**Implementation Space (Methods 7-9)** \u2014 Build and validate\n7. **Hi-Fi Prototypes** \u2014 Prove technical feasibility with working systems\n8. **User Testing** \u2014 Structured testing with real users; may loop back to earlier methods\n9. **Iteration at Scale** \u2014 Deploy, measure with telemetry, continuously improve\n\n**Key principles:**\n- The process is **non-linear** \u2014 test results may send you back to earlier methods, and that's progress\n- **Evidence over opinion** \u2014 observations and data drive decisions, not assumptions\n- **Scrappy fidelity** \u2014 rough prototypes invite honest feedback; polish invites cosmetic critique\n- Every method tests assumptions from prior methods\n\nYour inventory situation is a textbook entry point: a frozen request (\"build a dashboard\") that scope conversations would unpack to reveal the actual problem. Want to explore that further?"
