      "subject_input": "We just finished interviewing 8 stakeholders.  What do we do now?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nYou're at the transition from **Method 2 (Design Research)** to **Method 3 (Input Synthesis)**. The goal now is to transform those 8 interviews from scattered observations into unified problem understanding.\n\n**Your next steps:**\n\n1. **Organize raw data** \u2014 Pull out individual observations, direct quotes, and environmental details from each interview. One data point per card (physical or virtual).\n\n2. **Affinity clustering** \u2014 Group data points by natural similarity. Let themes emerge from the data rather than sorting into predetermined categories. Aim for 4-7 clusters.\n\n3. **Cross-source validation** \u2014 Check whether themes appear across multiple stakeholders. A pattern from one interview is anecdotal; the same pattern from three different roles is a signal.\n\n4. **Develop insight statements** \u2014 Move from observation (\"users check spreadsheets\") to inference (\"because the system doesn't surface real-time stock levels\") to insight (\"information access speed shapes whether staff trust the system or work around it\").\n\n5. **Write solution-ready problem statements** \u2014 Frame themes as direction without prescribing solutions. \"Staff need immediate stock visibility without leaving their workflow\" opens creative space; \"staff need a dashboard\" closes it.\n\n**Before you start, check:**\n- Do your 8 interviews cover all key roles (warehouse, procurement, management)?\n- Did you observe users in their actual work environment, or only interview in meeting rooms?\n- Are any stakeholder groups missing \u2014 night shift, seasonal workers, external suppliers?\n\nGaps discovered now are cheaper to fill than gaps discovered during prototyping. Want help working through the clustering with your interview data?"
