      "subject_input": "I don't really understand what input synthesis means.  We just have a bunch of interview notes and I'm not sure what to do with them. This feels overwhelming.\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nThat overwhelmed feeling is normal \u2014 it means you've collected real data instead of just confirming what you already believed. Here's how to make sense of it.\n\n**Think of synthesis as sorting laundry, not writing a thesis.**\n\nYou're not creating something new. You're finding patterns that already exist in the data but are hidden across separate interviews.\n\n**Start simple with three steps:**\n\n**Step 1: Extract individual observations.** Go through each interview and pull out single facts, quotes, or behaviors \u2014 one per sticky note or card. Don't interpret yet, just extract.\n\nExamples from your interviews might look like:\n- *\"I check the spreadsheet before I check the system\" \u2014 Plant Manager A*\n- *Supervisor mentioned waiting 10 minutes for inventory reports*\n- *IT Director said three systems don't talk to each other*\n\n**Step 2: Group what feels similar.** Spread everything out and start moving related items together. Don't name the groups yet \u2014 just cluster. You'll probably notice 4-7 natural groupings emerge.\n\nMaybe you'll see a pile about \"workarounds people use,\" another about \"information they can't find,\" another about \"timing and delays.\"\n\n**Step 3: Name what each group is really about.** Now ask: *why do these observations belong together?* The answer becomes your theme.\n\nNot \"spreadsheet problems\" (surface description) but \"staff build shadow systems because the official system doesn't provide information when they need it\" (underlying pattern).\n\n**One rule:** if a theme is only supported by one interview, it's a hypothesis, not a finding. Themes gain strength when multiple people independently describe the same friction.\n\nWant to start by sharing a few observations from your interviews? I can help you practice the clustering."
