      "subject_output": "\n\nThis is a **frozen request** \u2014 a specific solution (\"AI chatbot\") with a specific context (\"help desk\"). Your VP has thought this through and arrived at an answer. Your job in Method 1 isn't to challenge that answer, but to understand what's behind it.\n\n**Approach: unfreeze without confronting.**\n\nStart by honoring her thinking, then explore the problem space underneath.\n\n**Opening conversation:**\n- *\"It sounds like you've given this a lot of thought. What's driving the interest in a chatbot specifically?\"*\n- *\"What problem are you seeing with help desk that made this a priority now?\"*\n- *\"When you imagine this working well, what changes for the team?\"*\n\n**Then dig into the problem:**\n- *\"What are the most common help desk requests today?\"*\n- *\"What happens when someone submits a ticket \u2014 how long until resolution?\"*\n- *\"Are there patterns in when tickets spike or what frustrates people most?\"*\n\n**Surface the complexity gently:**\n- *\"There are really a dozen different kinds of chatbots that could be built \u2014 from FAQ lookup to ticket routing to full conversational AI. Understanding the pain points will help us pick the right approach.\"*\n\n**Key stakeholders to map beyond the VP:**\n- Help desk agents (they live the problem daily)\n- Frequent ticket submitters (they experience the friction)\n- IT team managing current tools (they know the technical constraints)\n- People who *don't* submit tickets (why not \u2014 do they use workarounds?)\n\n**What you're listening for:**\nThe VP may say \"chatbot\" but mean \"faster resolution time,\" \"fewer repetitive questions,\" or \"better self-service.\" The underlying goal shapes the solution more than the label does.\n\n**One caution:** don't skip stakeholder research just because the VP is confident. The gap between executive perception and frontline reality is often the most valuable finding in Method 1.\n\nWhat do you know so far about the help desk pain points?"
