      "subject_input": "We've completed our scope conversations and confirmed the problem is real.  Now we need to do design research.  We have access to 3 plant managers and about 20 floor operators.  How do we structure our research?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nHere's a research plan structured around your available participants:\n\n**Research Sequence**\n\nFollow the universal discovery order: observe first, then interview, then validate.\n\n**Phase 1: Environmental Observation (2-3 days)**\n\nSpend time on the floor *before* asking questions. Watch, don't talk.\n\n- Observe across at least 2 different shifts \u2014 day shift and off-hours operate differently\n- Note: how workers access inventory information, what tools they carry, physical conditions (noise, lighting, gloves, contamination), where they go when they need to know something\n- Watch for **workaround artifacts** \u2014 sticky notes on monitors, personal spreadsheets, hand signals, whiteboards with inventory counts\n\nThis phase reveals things workers have normalized and stopped mentioning.\n\n**Phase 2: Floor Operator Interviews (8-10 of your 20)**\n\nSelect for diversity, not convenience:\n\n| Selection Criteria | Why |\n|---|---|\n| 2-3 from day shift | Baseline experience with full support available |\n| 2-3 from night/weekend shift | Reduced support, different workarounds |\n| 1-2 new hires (<6 months) | Haven't adapted yet, feel the friction freshly |\n| 1-2 veterans (10+ years) | Carry institutional knowledge, built the workarounds |\n| 1 temp/seasonal worker | Excluded from informal knowledge networks |\n\n**Interview on the floor, not in a conference room.** The environment triggers questions neither of you would remember in a meeting room.\n\n**Opening questions:**\n- *\"Walk me through what happens when you need a part that isn't where it should be.\"*\n- *\"Show me how you find out what's in stock right now.\"*\n- *\"What do you do when the system says one thing and the shelf says another?\"*\n\n**Phase 3: Plant Manager Interviews (all 3)**\n\nInterview managers *after* floor operators \u2014 you'll arrive with ground-level context that sharpens your questions.\n\n- *\"What visibility gaps keep you up at night?\"*\n- *\"When supply chain problems hit production, how do you find out \u2014 and how fast?\"*\n- *\"Where do the plant managers' views differ from what your operators described?\"* (don't reveal specifics, test for awareness of the gap)\n\n**Phase 4: Constraint Validation (1 day)**\n\nReturn to the floor with specific findings to verify:\n- Replay what you heard to 2-3 operators: *\"I heard X is a common problem \u2014 does that match your experience?\"*\n- Test assumptions that surprised you\n\n**Practical tips:**\n- Schedule operator interviews during natural pauses, not production peaks\n- Respect PPE requirements and observation boundaries\n- Capture **direct quotes**, not paraphrased summaries \u2014 quotes carry synthesis better\n- Keep researcher interpretation separate from raw observation\n\n**What you'll hand off to synthesis:**\n- Observation logs with environmental details\n- 8-10 operator interviews with direct quotes\n- 3 manager interviews with strategic context\n- Validated constraint inventory\n\nThe gap between what managers describe and what floor staff experience is typically where your most valuable insights live. When are you planning to start the observations?"
