      "subject_input": "From brainstorming we picked our top 3 ideas: a tool-tracking tag system, a floor status dashboard, and a predictive maintenance alert.  How do we turn these into user concepts?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nGood \u2014 three ideas from three different themes. Now make them concrete enough for stakeholders to react to, while keeping them deliberately rough.\n\n**For each idea, build a concept card with four elements:**\n\n**1. Title (2-4 words)** \u2014 Immediately conveys the core idea\n\n**2. Description (1-2 sentences)** \u2014 What it does and how, without implementation detail\n\n**3. Purpose** \u2014 The one assumption this concept tests\n\n**4. Visualization prompt** \u2014 A stick-figure sketch showing the core interaction\n\n**Here are your three concepts drafted:**\n\n---\n\n**Concept 1: Tag & Find Tools**\n\n*Description:* Operators scan a station display to see which tools are nearby and where missing ones were last used, eliminating search time.\n\n*Tests the assumption:* Workers will check a system before physically searching if it's faster and accessible from their station.\n\n*Sketch:* Stick figure at a workstation glancing at a small screen showing three tool icons \u2014 two with checkmarks, one with an arrow pointing to \"Station 4.\"\n\n---\n\n**Concept 2: Floor Pulse Board**\n\n*Description:* Large displays at key floor locations show live production status, equipment state, and shift priorities \u2014 updated automatically, no login required.\n\n*Tests the assumption:* Supervisors and operators will use ambient visual information to coordinate if it's always visible and current.\n\n*Sketch:* Two stick figures on a factory floor looking up at a wall-mounted board showing three colored bars (green, yellow, red) next to simple machine icons.\n\n---\n\n**Concept 3: Maintenance Nudge**\n\n*Description:* Equipment sensors trigger timely alerts to maintenance crew when conditions suggest service is needed, aligned to actual production windows rather than fixed calendar schedules.\n\n*Tests the assumption:* Maintenance crews will respond to condition-based alerts if they arrive at actionable moments rather than competing with production pressure.\n\n*Sketch:* Stick figure near a machine, phone in hand showing an alert icon with text \"Line 2 \u2014 vibration rising \u2014 next break in 40 min.\"\n\n---\n\n**Next step: Validate with stakeholders using Silent Review**\n\n1. **Show each concept visual without explanation.** Ask: *\"What do you think this represents?\"*\n2. **Check comprehension.** Did they grasp it in 30 seconds? If not, the concept needs simplifying, not more explanation.\n3. **Identify gaps.** *\"What's missing? What would prevent this from working on your floor?\"*\n4. **Assess resonance.** *\"Which of these would change your day the most?\"*\n\nRun this with at least one operator, one supervisor, and one maintenance crew member. Each role will react differently, and that divergence is valuable data.\n\n**Evaluate each concept through three lenses:**\n\n| Lens | Key Question |\n|---|---|\n| Desirability | Do workers and supervisors actually want this? |\n| Feasibility | Can it work in 85+ dB noise, with gloves, on existing infrastructure? |\n| Viability | Does it create value across enough roles to justify investment? |\n\n**One caution:** \"Floor status dashboard\" appeared as a stakeholder request early in your research. Validate that the concept evolved beyond the original frozen request \u2014 does it solve the *discovered* communication gap, or just repackage the original ask?\n\nWhich stakeholders can you get in front of for the silent review?"
