      "subject_input": "Users loved the floor status dashboard concept.  We want to prototype it.  Should we start building it in React?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\n**No \u2014 not yet.** React is a Method 7 (hi-fi) decision. You're at Method 6 (lo-fi). Building in code right now is the most expensive way to discover that your layout is wrong, the information hierarchy doesn't match workflow, or the display location is unusable.\n\n**Start scrappy. Discover constraints first.**\n\n**Week 1 Lo-Fi Prototypes (hours to build, not days):**\n\n**Prototype A: Paper on the wall**\n- Print a large poster-sized mockup of the dashboard\n- Tape it to the wall *where it would actually go* on the floor\n- Stand where operators and supervisors actually stand\n- Can they read it from that distance? In that lighting? While walking past?\n\n**Prototype B: Slide on a TV**\n- Put a static PowerPoint slide on a large monitor mounted at the proposed location\n- Show three different information layouts across a shift\n- Which layout do people glance at? Which do they ignore?\n\n**Prototype C: Whiteboard simulation**\n- Have a person manually update a whiteboard with the same information the dashboard would show\n- Update it every 15 minutes for a full shift\n- Watch: do people check it? When? What do they look for first?\n\n**What you're testing (one assumption per prototype):**\n\n| Prototype | Assumption Being Tested |\n|---|---|\n| Paper on wall | Display is readable from actual viewing distance and lighting |\n| Slide on TV | Information hierarchy matches what workers look for first |\n| Whiteboard | People will actually change behavior when live status is visible |\n\n**What you'll discover that React can't tell you:**\n\n- Is the proposed location even visible from key workstations?\n- Do workers want line status, equipment state, or shift priorities first?\n- Does the display need to be different during shift handoff vs normal operation?\n- What happens when someone walks up close \u2014 do they need interactive detail?\n- Is noise too loud for any audio alert component?\n\n**These are the constraints that should *define* your React build, not be discovered during it.**\n\nThe whiteboard prototype is particularly powerful \u2014 if workers don't change behavior when a human updates real-time status manually, they won't change behavior for a digital version either. That's a finding worth $50,000 of avoided development.\n\nOnce lo-fi testing validates the what, where, and when, *then* React (or whatever technology) becomes the right conversation for Method 7.\n\nWhat spaces on the floor are you considering for display placement?"
