      "subject_input": "Our paper prototypes validated the dashboard layout.  Now we need to test whether we can actually pull real-time data from the PLCs on the floor.  We're moving to high-fidelity prototyping.\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nGood transition \u2014 you've moved from \"do people want this\" (Method 6) to \"can we actually build it\" (Method 7). The question is now technical feasibility under real-world conditions.\n\n**Test at least 2-3 technical approaches before committing:**\n\n**Approach A: Direct PLC Polling**\n- Connect directly via Modbus or EtherNet/IP\n- Read production counters, equipment state, cycle times\n- Lowest latency, but tightest coupling to plant infrastructure\n\n**Approach B: OPC-UA Gateway**\n- Middleware layer that abstracts PLC communication\n- Supports multiple PLC vendors through a single interface\n- More flexible, but adds a component to maintain\n\n**Approach C: Historian Tap**\n- Read from existing data historian if the plant has one\n- Minimal new infrastructure, but data may be seconds or minutes stale\n- Test whether \"real-time\" actually needs to be sub-second or if 30-second refresh is fine enough\n\n**Critical validation questions:**\n\n| Dimension | What to Test |\n|---|---|\n| Data availability | Which PLC registers contain the data your dashboard needs? Do they already exist or require new ladder logic? |\n| Update frequency | How fast do values change? Match refresh rate to actual need, not assumed need |\n| Network access | Can you reach PLCs from the display network? Segmentation, firewalls, VLANs? |\n| Reliability | What happens when a PLC goes offline? Does the dashboard show stale data or fail visibly? |\n| Security | Your controls engineer and IT security need to approve any PLC network access \u2014 this is non-negotiable |\n\n**Safety boundaries:**\n\n- **Read only.** Your prototype reads PLC data \u2014 it never writes to PLCs or interacts with safety systems\n- Test against a PLC simulator or test bench first if available\n- Coordinate timing with maintenance windows for any physical network connections\n- Document every data point you're reading and get controls engineering sign-off\n\n**Build the thinnest possible vertical slice:**\n\nPick **one production line** and **3-5 data points** that map to what your lo-fi prototype validated people actually look at first. Get those displaying on a screen at the validated location. That's your hi-fi prototype.\n\nDon't build the full dashboard. Build the proof that live PLC data can reach a display reliably, then validate with users.\n\n**Capture comparison data across approaches:**\n\n| Metric | Approach A | Approach B | Approach C |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Data latency | | | |\n| Setup complexity | | | |\n| Vendor dependency | | | |\n| IT security approval path | | | |\n| Failure mode behavior | | | |\n\n**Who to involve now:**\n- Controls/automation engineer (PLC access and safety)\n- IT/networking (network segmentation, firewall rules)\n- Plant manager (approval for floor-level testing)\n- 1-2 operators from your lo-fi testing (continuity of feedback)\n\nWhich PLC vendors are on the floor, and does the plant have an existing historian system?"
