      "subject_input": "We have a working prototype of the floor status dashboard pulling live PLC data.  We want to test it with operators at Plant B. How should we set up the user testing?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nYou're at Method 8 \u2014 structured user testing. The goal is evidence for go, iterate, or return-to-earlier-method decisions.\n\n**Test Design**\n\n**Participant Selection (8-10 operators):**\n\n| Profile | Count | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Day shift experienced (2+ years) | 2-3 | Baseline, have established workflows |\n| Day shift newer (<6 months) | 1-2 | Haven't adapted to workarounds yet |\n| Night/off-shift | 2-3 | Different conditions, less support available |\n| Shift supervisor | 1-2 | Uses information differently than operators |\n| Maintenance crew member | 1 | Validates maintenance alert relevance |\n\n**Test Scenarios (task-based, not opinion-based):**\n\n| Scenario | What You're Measuring |\n|---|---|\n| \"Your line just went yellow \u2014 what does that mean and what would you do?\" | Comprehension speed and action clarity |\n| \"You're starting your shift \u2014 use the dashboard to understand current floor state\" | Information hierarchy validation |\n| \"Equipment on Line 3 shows a warning \u2014 walk me through your response\" | Alert interpretation and workflow integration |\n| \"You need to hand off to the next shift \u2014 what would you communicate from what you see?\" | Shift handoff utility |\n\n**Question Protocol \u2014 Leap-Enabling Only**\n\nDon't ask: *\"Do you like the dashboard?\"* (gives you nothing)\n\nInstead, use progressive questioning:\n\n1. **Experience:** *\"Walk me through what just happened when you looked at the board.\"*\n2. **First why:** *\"What made you look at that section first?\"*\n3. **Second why:** *\"What information were you actually trying to get?\"*\n4. **Improvement:** *\"What should change to make this work better during your shift?\"*\n\n**Testing Conditions**\n\n| Requirement | Why |\n|---|---|\n| Test during live production, not downtime | Real noise, real pressure, real distractions |\n| Test across at least 2 shifts | Night shift experience differs fundamentally |\n| Test during a shift handoff | Handoff is where communication gaps live |\n| Observer stays quiet during tasks | Watch what they do, not what they say when asked |\n| No hints or corrections during testing | Confusion is data, not a problem to fix |\n\n**Capture Template (one per session):**\n\n```\nParticipant: [role, shift, experience level]\nScenario: [which task]\nEnvironment: [noise, lighting, other conditions]\n\nWhat they did first:\nWhere they hesitated:\nWhat they misunderstood:\nWorkarounds they attempted:\nWhat they said vs what they did:\nTime to complete task:\n```\n\n**After Testing \u2014 Interpret Honestly**\n\nRoute each finding to the right response:\n\n| Finding Type | Example | Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| Minor usability | \"Text is small from 3 meters\" | Iterate in Method 9 |\n| Information design | \"I looked for line status but found equipment alerts first\" | Adjust hierarchy, retest |\n| Concept gap | \"I don't understand why I'd check this instead of walking the line\" | Return to Method 5-6, rethink value proposition |\n| Research gap | \"This doesn't show what I actually need during changeover\" | Return to Method 2, targeted research |\n\n**The hardest discipline:** if testing reveals operators don't change behavior with the dashboard present, that's a Method 4 finding \u2014 the concept may need rethinking, not refinement. Don't optimize something people aren't using.\n\nWhen is your first test session scheduled?"
