      "subject_input": "User testing went well at Plant B.  Leadership wants to roll out the dashboard across all 5 plants.  How do we approach iteration at scale?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nCongratulations on validated testing results. Now the challenge shifts from \"does it work\" to \"does it work everywhere, for everyone, sustainably.\" This is Method 9 territory.\n\n**Don't copy-paste Plant B across five plants.** Each plant has different equipment, culture, and workflows. Roll out in phases with learning between each.\n\n**Phase 1: Establish Baselines (before rollout)**\n\nMeasure the current state at each plant so you can prove impact later:\n\n| Metric | What to Capture | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| Information lookup time | How long do operators spend finding status information today? | Your primary value claim |\n| Shift handoff duration | How long does handoff take and what gets lost? | Dashboard should improve this |\n| Response time to issues | Time from equipment problem to first human response | Leading indicator of dashboard value |\n| Existing workarounds | Whiteboards, spreadsheets, radio patterns in use today | Workaround retirement signals adoption |\n\n**Phase 2: Phased Rollout**\n\n| Phase | Scope | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| Month 1 | Plant B fully instrumented (your pilot) | Establish telemetry, validate measurement approach |\n| Month 2-3 | One additional plant (choose most different from B) | Discover what doesn't transfer \u2014 different PLCs, layout, culture |\n| Month 4-6 | Remaining three plants | Apply lessons from first two, customize per plant |\n\n**Why the second plant matters most:** pick the plant *least* like Plant B \u2014 different PLC vendor, different layout, different shift culture. What breaks there teaches you what to prepare for at the remaining three.\n\n**Phase 3: Telemetry Design**\n\nInstrument the dashboard itself to learn from real usage:\n\n| Data Point | What It Reveals |\n|---|---|\n| Screen views per hour by shift | When do people actually look at it? |\n| Which sections get viewed first | Does real usage match your intended hierarchy? |\n| Peak usage times | Shift changes? Equipment alerts? Start of shift? |\n| Feature usage frequency | What's valuable vs what's ignored? |\n| Time-on-screen patterns | Glance vs study \u2014 different information needs |\n\n**The discovery you can only make post-deployment:** Plant B testing showed how operators *try* the dashboard. Telemetry shows how they *live* with it over weeks and months.\n\n**Phase 4: Change Management Per Plant**\n\nTechnical deployment is the easy part. Adoption is the hard part.\n\n| Activity | Timing |\n|---|---|\n| Identify 1-2 champions per shift at each plant | Before installation |\n| Shift-overlap training (15 min, on the floor, not in a classroom) | During installation week |\n| Champions collect peer feedback for first 2 weeks | Post-installation |\n| Plant-specific customization based on feedback | Week 3-4 |\n| Measure against baselines | Month 2 at each plant |\n\n**Don't train in a conference room.** Walk to the display, show three scenarios, let them ask questions where they'll actually use it.\n\n**Phase 5: Continuous Improvement Cadence**\n\n| Frequency | Activity |\n|---|---|\n| Weekly | Review telemetry for anomalies \u2014 usage drop, spike, unexpected patterns |\n| Monthly | Compare metrics against baselines, prioritize one improvement |\n| Quarterly | Deeper review \u2014 are workarounds retiring? Are new ones emerging? |\n| Annually | Revisit with user research \u2014 has the problem evolved? |\n\n**Watch for these signals:**\n\n| Signal | What It Means |\n|---|---|\n| Usage drops after week 2 | Initial novelty faded, value proposition isn't sticky |\n| Night shift usage significantly lower | Different needs or conditions not addressed |\n| Workarounds persist alongside dashboard | Dashboard doesn't answer their actual question |\n| New workarounds emerge | Dashboard created new friction you didn't anticipate |\n| Shift handoff duration unchanged | Dashboard isn't integrated into handoff ritual |\n\n**One critical mindset shift:** you're no longer designing \u2014 you're operating and iterating. Small validated improvements beat large redesigns. Each change gets a hypothesis, a measurement, and a result before the next change ships.\n\nWhich plant is most different from Plant B? That's your second deployment target."
