      "subject_input": "We're trying to do input synthesis on our interview notes but I have no idea where to start.  I'm totally lost.\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nThat's okay \u2014 feeling lost is normal at this stage. It means you've collected real data instead of just confirming assumptions. Let's make it manageable with one small step at a time.\n\n**Step 1: Don't synthesize. Just extract.**\n\nOpen your first interview notes. Read through and pull out individual statements \u2014 one per line. Don't think about patterns yet. Just capture what people said and what you observed.\n\nExamples of what to extract:\n- A direct quote: *\"I check three different systems before I trust the inventory count\"*\n- A behavior you observed: *Operator walked 200 feet to visually confirm stock level*\n- A fact: *Night shift has no supervisor coverage from 2-4 AM*\n- A frustration: *Maintenance tech said work orders arrive after the problem is already fixed*\n\n**That's it for Step 1.** Repeat for each interview. You'll end up with a big list \u2014 maybe 50-100 individual data points. That's good.\n\n**Step 2: Print, cut, spread.**\n\nPut each data point on its own sticky note or index card. If you're digital, one item per cell in a spreadsheet works.\n\nSpread them all out on a table or wall where you can see everything at once.\n\n**Step 3: Move what feels similar together.**\n\nDon't name groups yet. Don't create categories in advance. Just physically move items that feel related near each other. Trust your gut.\n\nYou might notice:\n- A pile about \"checking multiple sources for the same information\"\n- A pile about \"things that work differently on night shift\"\n- A pile about \"workarounds people invented\"\n- Some items that don't fit anywhere \u2014 that's fine, leave them loose\n\n**Step 4: Ask \"why do these belong together?\"**\n\nLook at each pile. The answer to *why* becomes your theme name.\n\n| Not This (surface label) | This (underlying pattern) |\n|---|---|\n| \"System complaints\" | \"Staff don't trust the system so they verify everything manually\" |\n| \"Night shift problems\" | \"Knowledge that's available informally during the day disappears after hours\" |\n| \"Communication issues\" | \"Information travels through people, not systems, so it breaks at shift boundaries\" |\n\n**Step 5: Count your sources.**\n\nFor each theme, check: how many *different* interviews support it? A theme from one person is a hypothesis. A theme from four people across different roles is a finding.\n\n**Start with Step 1 right now.** Pick one interview and extract 10-15 individual data points. Don't worry about the other steps yet.\n\nHow many interviews do you have to work through?"
