      "subject_input": "We've been talking about our interview findings and I just had an idea for a solution \u2014 what if we put QR codes on every tool so operators can scan them to check availability?\n",
      "subject_output": "\n\nGood creative instinct \u2014 but notice what just happened. You're in synthesis (Method 3), and a solution idea pulled you forward to Method 4 territory. That's natural, and the idea might be great, but acting on it now carries risk.\n\n**Why to park it, not lose it:**\n\nIf you pursue QR codes now, you'll design everything around that approach and unconsciously filter your remaining synthesis to support it. You'll miss themes that point to completely different \u2014 possibly better \u2014 solutions.\n\n**What to do right now:**\n\nWrite it on a parking lot \u2014 a visible list of solution ideas to revisit during brainstorming. One line is enough:\n\n*\"QR codes on tools for scan-to-check availability\"*\n\nThen come back to your synthesis with fresh eyes.\n\n**The idea also has embedded assumptions worth noting for later:**\n\n| Assumption | Question to Test |\n|---|---|\n| Operators have a device to scan with | Do they? On every shift? Is it accessible with full hands? |\n| QR codes survive the floor environment | Grease, heat, impact, cleaning chemicals \u2014 will codes stay readable? |\n| Scanning is faster than current workarounds | Is it faster than shouting \"where's the torque wrench?\" |\n| The problem is *finding* tools | Or is it that tools aren't *returned*? QR codes track location, not behavior |\n| Operators will adopt scanning | 15% adoption on your safety checklist app suggests this isn't guaranteed |\n\nThat last point connects to your earlier experience. Understanding *why* the safety app was ignored should inform any solution requiring operators to interact with a device.\n\n**When to revisit this idea:**\n\nDuring Method 4 brainstorming, bring it off the parking lot alongside other ideas. It becomes one of many approaches to evaluate rather than the approach you've already committed to. It may survive, merge with something better, or get replaced entirely.\n\nWhat themes are emerging from your synthesis so far?"
