      "subject_output": "\n\nGreat \u2014 let's set the foundation with Method 1 scope conversations.\n\n**First, classify your request:**\n\n\"Improving the warehouse picking process\" is **fluid** \u2014 you have a problem area but no predetermined solution. That's a healthy starting point because it leaves room for genuine discovery.\n\n**Before talking to anyone, map who to talk to:**\n\n| Tier | Role | What They'll Reveal |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary | Pickers (floor workers) | Actual daily experience, workarounds, physical constraints |\n| Primary | Pick team leads/supervisors | Workflow oversight, shift variation, exception handling |\n| Secondary | Warehouse manager | Performance metrics, strategic priorities, known pain points |\n| Secondary | Receiving/replenishment staff | How stock gets to pick locations, upstream dependencies |\n| Secondary | Shipping/packing | Downstream impact of picking errors and delays |\n| Hidden | IT/systems | WMS capabilities, integration constraints, data quality |\n| Hidden | Customers/customer service | What picking problems look like from the outside |\n| Hidden | Temporary/seasonal workers | Onboarding friction, process clarity for non-experts |\n\n**Start with 3-4 scope conversations:**\n\nTalk to the warehouse manager and 1-2 supervisors first to understand the landscape. Then talk to 2-3 pickers to start hearing the ground-level reality.\n\n**Opening questions:**\n\n- *\"Walk me through what a typical pick run looks like from start to finish.\"*\n- *\"When things go wrong during picking, what usually causes it?\"*\n- *\"What's the difference between a good day and a bad day in picking?\"*\n- *\"If you could change one thing about the current process, what would it be \u2014 and why that one?\"*\n\n**Key things to listen for:**\n\n| Signal | What It Suggests |\n|---|---|\n| Specific technology or tool requests | Frozen solution embedded in a fluid problem \u2014 dig into the *why* |\n| \"We've always done it this way\" | Process inertia worth investigating |\n| Different answers from managers vs pickers | Gap between perceived and actual workflow |\n| Workarounds mentioned casually | Unmet needs the current system doesn't address |\n| Complaints about the same thing from multiple people | Early theme signal for Method 3 |\n\n**Environmental factors to note for later:**\n\nWarehouse conditions directly shape what solutions are viable \u2014 lighting, temperature, noise levels, device access, glove requirements, distance walked, cart/equipment constraints. You'll observe these in Method 2, but note anything mentioned during scope conversations.\n\nWho do you have access to for initial conversations?"
