      "subject_input": "We have a brand new project to rethink how field technicians report equipment failures.  We haven't done any design thinking on this yet.  Project slug is \"field-failure-reporting\".  I'm the product manager and my team is 4 engineers plus a UX designer.  We have about an hour today.\n",
      "subject_output": "Info: /Users/eugenefedorenko/work/hve-core/.copilot-tracking/dt/field-failure-reporting/coaching-state.mdProject initialized. You're at **Method 1: Scope Conversations** \u2014 and \"rethink how field technicians report equipment failures\" is a **fluid request**, which is a great starting point. No frozen solution to unpack.\n\nWith one hour today, let's use it to build your scope foundation. Here's what we can accomplish:\n\n**Today's goal: Answer three questions**\n\n**1. What do you already know?**\n- What triggers this project now \u2014 is reporting broken, too slow, inaccurate, or something else?\n- How do field techs report failures today?\n- Who receives those reports, and what happens next?\n\n**2. Who's in the stakeholder ecosystem?**\n\nStart mapping \u2014 who should your team eventually talk to?\n\n| Tier | Likely Roles |\n|---|---|\n| Primary | Field technicians, dispatch/coordination |\n| Secondary | Service managers, engineering (receive reports), parts/logistics |\n| Hidden | Customers on-site during repairs, back-office data entry, compliance/safety |\n\n**3. What assumptions does your team hold?**\n\nHave each of your 4 engineers and UX designer independently write down: *\"I think the main problem with failure reporting is...\"* \u2014 don't discuss yet, just capture. Comparing those answers reveals where the team agrees and where you're guessing.\n\nLet's start with what you know: what does the current reporting process look like, and what's making it a problem worth solving right now?"
