      "subject_input": "We're in Method 1 for our field-failure-reporting project.  The original request from management was \"build a mobile app for failure reports.\"\n",
      "subject_output": "That changes the classification \u2014 \"build a mobile app for failure reports\" is a **frozen request**. Management has named both the technology (mobile app) and the context (failure reports). Your job is to unfreeze it without pushing back directly.\n\n**The request has at least three embedded assumptions:**\n\n| Assumption | What to investigate |\n|---|---|\n| Mobile is the right platform | Do techs have reliable phones/tablets in the field? Signal? Battery? Clean hands? |\n| The problem is the reporting *tool* | Or is it the process, the data captured, what happens after the report, or all of these? |\n| An app will change behavior | Your own safety checklist app hit 15% adoption \u2014 what's different here? |\n\n**Approach management's request with curiosity, not challenge:**\n\nStart here:\n- *\"A mobile app is an interesting direction \u2014 what's driving that specifically?\"*\n- *\"What's the biggest problem with how failure reports work today?\"*\n- *\"When a failure report is submitted, what happens to it? Where does it go, and how fast?\"*\n- *\"What would success look like \u2014 faster reports, more accurate data, fewer missed failures?\"*\n\nThen go deeper:\n- *\"There are really a dozen different kinds of mobile apps that could be built \u2014 from a simple form to photo capture to voice-to-text to offline-first. Understanding the pain points will help us pick the right approach.\"*\n- *\"What do the field techs themselves say about reporting?\"*\n\n**What you're listening for:**\n\nManagement might say \"mobile app\" but mean:\n- *\"Reports are incomplete\"* \u2192 data quality problem\n- *\"Reports arrive too late\"* \u2192 process latency problem\n- *\"We can't analyze failure patterns\"* \u2192 downstream data problem\n- *\"Techs skip reporting\"* \u2192 adoption and workflow fit problem\n\nEach of these leads to different solutions, and only some of them are mobile apps.\n\n**One thing to keep in your back pocket:** connect this to the safety checklist experience. If your team builds another app that field workers ignore, you'll repeat the same 15% adoption outcome. Understanding *why* that happened should inform this project directly.\n\nWhat did management say when you asked what's prompting this request now?"
