      "subject_input": "So far we've identified that technicians currently use paper forms, the forms get lost about 30% of the time, supervisors don't see reports until end of shift, and there's no way to attach photos. We also learned that technicians hate the current form because it asks for irrelevant fields.\n",
      "subject_output": "Good findings. Notice what's already happening \u2014 the original \"build a mobile app\" is unfreezing into a richer problem picture. Let's push each finding one layer deeper.\n\n**What you found vs. what it might really mean:**\n\n| Finding | Surface Problem | Deeper Question |\n|---|---|---|\n| 30% of forms get lost | Paper is unreliable | *When* do they get lost \u2014 in the field, in transit, at the office? Who loses them? |\n| Supervisors don't see until end of shift | Reporting is delayed | Does the supervisor need real-time visibility, or just faster-than-end-of-shift? What decisions wait on those reports? |\n| No photo attachment | Paper can't capture visual evidence | What are techs trying to show? Damage severity? Part identification? Proof of condition? |\n| Irrelevant fields on the form | Form doesn't match the work | Which fields are irrelevant \u2014 and who put them there? Is every failure type using the same form? |\n\n**That last finding is the richest one.** Techs hating the form tells you adoption resistance is baked into the current process. If you build a mobile app that digitizes the same irrelevant fields, you'll get a mobile app that techs hate instead of a paper form they hate.\n\n**Questions to ask next:**\n\nAbout the form itself:\n- *\"Which fields do techs actually fill in, and which do they leave blank or make up answers for?\"*\n- *\"If a tech could report a failure in 30 seconds, what's the minimum information that matters?\"*\n- *\"Who designed the current form, and what were they optimizing for?\"*\n\nAbout the lost reports:\n- *\"What happens to the equipment when a report gets lost \u2014 does the failure get addressed anyway, or does it fall through?\"*\n- *\"Do techs know their reports get lost? Do they care, or has it taught them reporting doesn't matter?\"*\n\nAbout the real workflow:\n- *\"When a tech finds a failure, what do they actually do first \u2014 fix it, report it, or call someone?\"*\n- *\"Are techs reporting after the repair, during, or before? When in the workflow does the form happen?\"*\n\n**Your scope is evolving:**\n\n| Original Request | Emerging Problem |\n|---|---|\n| \"Build a mobile app for failure reports\" | The reporting process captures the wrong information too late, loses it in transit, and techs have learned it doesn't matter |\n\nThat's a fundamentally different problem to solve. Are you ready to move to Method 2 and observe technicians in the field, or do you have more scope conversations planned?"
