      "subject_input": "I think we've done enough scope conversations for the field-failure-reporting project.  We talked to 6 stakeholders and identified that the core problem is delayed visibility into equipment health, not the reporting form itself.  Let's move on.\n",
      "subject_output": "Good work \u2014 the problem evolved significantly from \"build a mobile app\" to \"delayed visibility into equipment health.\" That gap between the original request and the discovered problem is exactly what Method 1 is for.\n\n**Moving to Method 2: Design Research**\n\nYou need to see and hear how technicians actually experience equipment failures in the field. Your scope conversations told you what stakeholders *think* happens \u2014 research reveals what *actually* happens.\n\n**Research plan for your team of 6:**\n\n**Phase 1: Field Observation (before any interviews)**\n\nSend your UX designer and one engineer to shadow 2-3 technicians during actual service calls. Watch silently for the first 30 minutes before asking anything.\n\nDocument:\n- When a tech discovers a failure, what do they do *first* \u2014 fix it, report it, call someone?\n- Where is the paper form relative to the work? Truck, clipboard, pocket, left behind?\n- What's the physical environment \u2014 weather, lighting, noise, gloves, dirty hands?\n- What devices do they carry and actually use in the field?\n- How do they communicate with dispatch and supervisors right now?\n\n**Phase 2: Technician Interviews (4-6 techs)**\n\nSelect for diversity:\n\n| Profile | Why |\n|---|---|\n| 2 experienced techs (5+ years) | Built workarounds, carry institutional knowledge |\n| 1-2 newer techs (<1 year) | Feel friction that veterans have normalized |\n| 1 tech from a different region/territory | Conditions and culture may differ |\n\n**Key questions:**\n- *\"Walk me through the last equipment failure you responded to \u2014 from the moment you arrived.\"*\n- *\"When you find something wrong that isn't what you were called for, what do you do?\"*\n- *\"Show me what you actually do with the paper form.\"*\n- *\"How do you know if anyone ever reads your reports?\"*\n\n**Phase 3: Downstream Interviews (2-3 sessions)**\n\nTalk to whoever *receives* the reports:\n- *\"When a failure report arrives, what do you do with it?\"*\n- *\"What information is always missing that you wish you had?\"*\n- *\"How do you currently detect patterns across multiple failures?\"*\n\n**What to watch for specifically, given your scope findings:**\n\nThe problem is \"delayed visibility\" \u2014 so your research should reveal *where time gets lost* in the chain from failure discovery to organizational awareness. Map every handoff point.\n\nHow soon can your team get into the field with technicians?"
